__NOTOC__ __NOEDITSECTION__ <big>''See [[Help:Collections]] for more information.''</big> == Using the collection creator == After the ''collection creator'' has been enabled, the box as seen below is shown above each wiki page. {| |- | [[File:Collection Extension - Create a collection box.png|frame|The collection creator interface]] |- |}
;''Add this page to your collection'' :Adds the currently viewed page to your collection. ;''Show collection'' :Opens a new page which will show a list of all pages that you added to your collection. On that page, you can '''change the order''' of the pages in your collection and '''structure''' them using chapters. Further, you can '''download''' the books as a [[w:PDF|PDF]] or [[w:OpenDocument|ODF]], or order a '''printed book'''. ;''Suggest pages'' :This tool analyzes the current set of pages in your book and '''suggests''' pages that might be also relevant to the overall topic of your collection. This tool allows to create collections '''quickly'''. ;''Disable'' :This will '''disable''' the ''Collection creator'' and '''delete''' your collection (unless you saved it first).
=== Adding pages without visiting them === A quick way to add pages is to simply hover on a linked page. If you wait about one second, a small box will pop up with the message "Add linked wiki page to your collection". Click on this link, and the linked page will be added to your collection.
{| |- | [[File:Collection Extension - Hover and add page.png|frame|Hovering your mouse over links is a convenient way to add pages to your collection]] |- |}
=== Adding whole categories === If you are viewing a [[Wikibooks:Categories|category page]], you can add all the pages in that category at once. The ''Add this page to your collection'' link will have changed into ''Add this category to your collection''. Click on this new link, and all the pages in that category will be added to your collection. Relevant categories may be found at the very bottom of Wikibooks pages. Categories can also be added by hovering category links.

'''Napoleon's theorem''' (so called because some people have attributed it to Napoleon Bonaparte) states that if any triangle is taken, and an equilateral triangle constructed on each side, pointing outwards, the centroids of these three triangles are the vertices of an equilateral triangle.

The theorem is easily proved by calculating the separations of the centroids and showing that they are equal.

